II, that made the claim that the dropping of those bombs was NOT neccassary and was in fact an act of revenge.<br><br>Before I start, in order to JUDGE whether an act was made for one reason or another, one must look at WHAT information was available at the TIME of the descision. It doesnt matter what information becomes available AFTER the fact.<br><br>Facts that are not disputable by Revisionist History.<br><br>1.  On Saipan, the first Island in Pacific war that had a sizable Japanese civilian population, as the Japanese Army was losing and it became clear the Island would fall to American forces, hundreds of Japanese Civilians committed suicide rather than be &quot;captured&quot; by the American forces. Families jumped from cliffs to their death even as captured Japanese prisoners and American Linguists attempted to convince them otherwise. women and children committed suicide to avoid capture.<br><br>2. On Okinawa, the First civilian populated island of Japan (yes I know okinawians disagree about that status), thousands of civilians commited suicide rather than surrender to American forces. Again even though Linguists and captured prisoners tried to convince them otherwise.<br><br>Facts I doubt were skewed by Revisionist History <br><br>1. The Japanese Army had a tradition of NOT surrendering. This lead to FEW prisoners before the major island assaults in the Pacific.<br><br>2. The Japanese Government was attempting to mobilize every male able to, to defend the Main Islands of Japan.<br><br>President Truman was FACED with the above Facts. He also was informed by his Military advisors that the projected causalties to the Invading Forces would top 100,000 killed and closer to 1 million when wounded where included. These causalties were projected if the Japanese refused to surrender and fought for all the Islands of Japan.<br><br>The stubborn refusal of the Japanese High Command to Surrender and its continued resistance, INCLUDING the use of Suicide bomb laden planes, spoke of a real possibility of such losses being incurred. Also the plans needed to invade the Main islands would take till early 1946 to be drawn and staffed and prepared. Another Year of War.<br><br>Faced with the knowledge of civilian suicides in staggering numbers and a refusal of the Japanese to admit defeat, some advisors told President Truman it was a possibility that the Japanese people would basicly be committing Geonicide if invaded. At the very least the information indicated that MILLIONS of Japanese would die when the Main Islands were invaded. And there was no attempt by the Japanese Government to surrender. In fact the Military was exalting its troops to fight harder and for the civilian population to aid it.<br><br>All Targets selected for possible use of the Atomic bombs WERE military in nature. While all were Based in Civilain centers (cities) EACH was for the most part an Army Headquarters with assigned troops and training facilities to raise, equip and send into combat troops. Most if not all had been spared fire bombing partly because of the potential to demostrate the effectiveness of an atomic bomb on the Leadership of Japan.<br><br>This is what President Truman was faced with (in part) when he had to decide whether to drop those bombs. The targets were Military in nature and not designated civilain.<br><br>It is a FACT that the dropping of the second bomb was followed shortly by the Japanese surrender. No invasion was needed and thousands of Allied troops were saved. Based on the previous incidents of the actions of the Japanese in the Pacific it is arguable that MILLIONS of Japanese were saved.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utarunwarspirit.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tarun Warspirit</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.circleoftheancient.com/tarunlogo.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <